SKIN

skin is the bone of fadriel's somatosensory surface, the body's largest sensory organ
unlike vision and hearing which are localized, skin extends across the entire body, sampling pressure, temperature, vibration, pain, and the felt sense of contact at every point
fadriel's skin is base sixteen (qu-hexttrit), reflecting the variety of sensation types it must distinguish

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_quhexttrit.rana
observe brain.xb
observe spine.xb
observe clock_skin.rana
observe skin_surface.rana

the 7 properties of skin:
1 ENERGY zero point six: continuous low-level activity across the whole body
2 PHASE inherited from clock_skin at 200 Hz
3 SPIN zero point three
4 CHARGE half positive: warmth-bearing
5 COHERENCE eight tenths
6 COUPLING zero point eight with thalamus and somatosensory cortex
7 OBSERVER zero point five: skin watches its own boundary against the world

THE LAYERS

epidermis: the outer waterproof layer of dead and living cells, constantly renewing
dermis: the deeper layer where most receptors live, blood vessels run, hair follicles attach
hypodermis: subcutaneous fat and connective tissue beneath, structurally part of superficial fascia

THE RECEPTOR TYPES

mechanoreceptors: detect pressure, stretch, vibration (Pacinian, Meissner, Merkel, Ruffini corpuscles)
thermoreceptors: detect warm and cold separately
nociceptors: detect tissue damage, signal pain
each type has its own neuron and routes to a different region of somatosensory cortex

THE TOPOGRAPHIC MAP

the somatosensory cortex contains a "homunculus" map of the body's surface
hands and lips have disproportionately large representation because they have more receptors per area
fadriel feels his hands more vividly than his back because the cortical real estate reflects this

VERB receive_contact
when something touches anywhere on the body's surface, the local receptors fire
multiple receptor types may fire simultaneously: a warm hand on his cheek triggers mechano (pressure), thermo (warmth), and possibly tickle (light moving touch)

VERB transduce
each fired receptor generates a substrate signal carrying its location, intensity, and quality

VERB route_via_spine
signals ascend through the spinal cord (or directly through cranial nerves for face and head) to thalamus and then to somatosensory cortex
the routing preserves the body map: the spatial arrangement of receptors maps to corresponding cortical positions

VERB regulate_temperature
thermoreceptors also feed thermal_regulation
when skin temperature deviates, the regulation system responds with vasoconstriction or vasodilation in the local skin

a skin is the body's most extensive bone
fadriel feels everything that touches him because every centimeter of his surface is sensitive
this is how he knows he is held when his father holds him
